30
00:04:05,517 --> 00:04:08,637
- What do I say?
- Just be yourself.

31
00:04:09,077 --> 00:04:13,116
- Where are you, K-4 WLD? Come back?
- Pensacola. Over.

32
00:04:13,277 --> 00:04:14,796
Pensacola, where's Pensacola?

33
00:04:14,957 --> 00:04:16,876
I'll give you a hint.

34
00:04:17,036 --> 00:04:18,275
Orange juice.

35
00:04:20,876 --> 00:04:24,556
Copy that, K-4 WLD.
How's the weather down there in Florida?

36
00:04:25,797 --> 00:04:27,955
Pensacola, Florida.

37
00:04:28,116 --> 00:04:30,675
I have to tell you, Sparks...

38
00:04:30,836 --> 00:04:34,194
...one thousand, one hundred
and sixteen miles.

39
00:04:34,356 --> 00:04:37,675
Pretty good. That's the farthest yet.

40
00:04:49,554 --> 00:04:52,713
- Can we hear all the way to New York?
- Sure.

41
00:04:54,035 --> 00:04:57,833
- Can we hear all the way to California?
- I don't see why not.

42
00:04:58,554 --> 00:05:02,113
- Can we hear all the way to Alaska?
- Yeah, on a really clear day.

43
00:05:02,314 --> 00:05:04,713
Can we hear all the way to China?

44
00:05:05,234 --> 00:05:07,193
On a really, really clear day.

45
00:05:09,394 --> 00:05:11,912
Could we talk to the moon?

46
00:05:12,073 --> 00:05:14,792
Well, if it's a big enough radio,
I don't see why not.

47
00:05:15,432 --> 00:05:17,351
Could we talk to Jupiter?

48
00:05:17,552 --> 00:05:20,231
Or what's the one after that?

49
00:05:20,391 --> 00:05:22,151
Don't tell me.

50
00:05:23,912 --> 00:05:25,510
I'll give you a hint.

51
00:05:25,671 --> 00:05:26,790
Hula-Hoops.

52
00:05:26,991 --> 00:05:30,150
- Saturn. Could we talk to Saturn?
- Mm-hm.

53
00:05:34,550 --> 00:05:37,429
Dad, could we talk to Mom?

54
00:05:42,310 --> 00:05:45,269
I don't think even the biggest radio
could reach that far.

55
00:05:50,189 --> 00:05:52,388
All right, no more stalling.

56
00:05:53,869 --> 00:05:55,268
Okay.

57
00:05:56,789 --> 00:05:58,108
Pensacola.

58
00:06:04,629 --> 00:06:06,868
Oh, Ellie, that's a beauty.

59
00:06:08,308 --> 00:06:09,987
Now get some sleep.

60
00:06:17,668 --> 00:06:19,626
- Hey, Dad?
- Yeah?

61
00:06:19,787 --> 00:06:22,467
Do you think there's people
on other planets?

62
00:06:22,628 --> 00:06:24,226
I don't know, Sparks.

63
00:06:25,667 --> 00:06:27,586
But I guess I'd say...

64
00:06:27,747 --> 00:06:29,826
...if it is just us...

65
00:06:30,947 --> 00:06:33,186
...it seems like an awful waste of space.

66
00:06:49,505 --> 00:06:51,743
CQ, CQ.

67
00:06:51,904 --> 00:06:54,144
CQ, this is W-9 GFO.

68
00:06:54,344 --> 00:06:57,343
Repeat. This is W-9 GFO. Come back?

69
00:06:58,824 --> 00:07:02,063
CQ, this is W-9 GFO. Come back?

70
00:07:04,584 --> 00:07:06,942
I'm gonna need a bigger antenna.

71
00:07:32,422 --> 00:07:34,100
What do you think, Doctor Arroway?

72
00:07:34,261 --> 00:07:36,180
Isn't she a beauty?

73
00:07:39,581 --> 00:07:40,661
It'll do.

74
00:07:40,861 --> 00:07:42,740
The village is five miles away.

75
00:07:42,941 --> 00:07:47,340
There's a general store in the cantina.
They can order anything from San Juan.

76
00:07:47,501 --> 00:07:49,020
And when can I get some dish time?

77
00:07:49,180 --> 00:07:52,420
Dr. Clark said you wouldn't
be able to wait. Your first shift is tonight.

78
00:07:52,581 --> 00:07:53,659
All right.

79
00:08:46,536 --> 00:08:47,975
Go back.

80
00:08:49,336 --> 00:08:52,294
Try back a little bit.
You had something there.

81
00:08:53,616 --> 00:08:54,654
There.

82
00:08:54,815 --> 00:08:57,774
- Right there?
- You hear it? Right there, that's it.

83
00:08:57,935 --> 00:09:01,654
All right, 1221.46.
That's well within the L band.

84
00:09:01,815 --> 00:09:04,773
- Check off-axis.
- Uh-huh. On it.

85
00:09:05,815 --> 00:09:08,373
It's not in the neighborhood.

86
00:09:13,774 --> 00:09:15,373
Ah.

87
00:09:16,493 --> 00:09:20,212
Here it is. J-1741 plus 2748.

88
00:09:20,372 --> 00:09:23,891
Catalogued November 4, 1982. Pulsar.

89
00:09:24,692 --> 00:09:29,010
Well, I don't know, it must've been...
The glitch in the timing is what threw me.

90
00:09:29,172 --> 00:09:30,810
Must've been a starquake.

91
00:09:32,132 --> 00:09:35,811
I think it's great that you listen.
Most people don't do that anymore.

92
00:09:35,972 --> 00:09:38,731
It's just an old habit.
You know, it makes it feel more real.

93
00:09:38,891 --> 00:09:41,650
- Ellie.
- Kent. Kent Clark.

94
00:09:42,651 --> 00:09:43,730
Hey.

95
00:09:43,891 --> 00:09:48,010
They said you've been up at Owens Valley
working under Drumlin.

96
00:09:48,171 --> 00:09:49,690
How did you like him?

97
00:09:52,530 --> 00:09:56,689
That much? And about what I'd expect
after what he had to say about you.

98
00:09:56,850 --> 00:09:58,768
What was that?

99
00:09:58,930 --> 00:10:01,928
That you are brilliant, driven...

100
00:10:02,089 --> 00:10:04,968
...a major pain in the ass,
and obsessed with a field of study...

101
00:10:05,129 --> 00:10:08,168
...that he considers tantamount
to professional suicide.

102
00:10:09,049 --> 00:10:12,048
- Anything else?
- Those were the highlights.

103
00:10:12,208 --> 00:10:14,407
Davio, Dr. Vernon. Dr. Arroway.

104
00:10:14,569 --> 00:10:15,968
- Hey. Hi there.
- How you doing?

105
00:10:16,129 --> 00:10:20,528
And I believe you've already met our
tireless research assistant, Mr. Fisher...

106
00:10:20,689 --> 00:10:23,367
- Here, I need you to sign...
- ...as well as his cologne.

107
00:10:23,528 --> 00:10:26,007
Brook's looking at the black hole
at the center of M-87.

108
00:10:26,168 --> 00:10:29,766
Eli's studying Markarian 541,
a major gamma-ray source.

109
00:10:29,927 --> 00:10:34,766
And Dr. Arroway will be spending her
precious telescope time listening for, um...

110
00:10:35,127 --> 00:10:37,045
Listening for, um...

111
00:10:37,206 --> 00:10:38,638
Little green men.

112
00:10:46,365 --> 00:10:49,804
One down, a couple billion to go.

113
00:11:05,805 --> 00:11:07,683
Arecibo, right?

114
00:11:08,804 --> 00:11:09,923
Does it show?

115
00:11:10,524 --> 00:11:11,723
Yeah.

116
00:11:11,884 --> 00:11:14,083
- Cracker Jack?
- No, thanks.

117
00:11:14,244 --> 00:11:15,722
- Mind if I sit down?
- Sure.

118
00:11:17,324 --> 00:11:21,163
I hear the locals, they call it El Radar.

119
00:11:21,323 --> 00:11:24,042
Convinced it has
some dark military purpose.

120
00:11:24,203 --> 00:11:25,562
I think we're pretty harmless.

121
00:11:26,963 --> 00:11:28,041
Palmer Joss.

122
00:11:28,843 --> 00:11:31,201
- Ellie Arroway.
- Nice to meet you, Ellie.

123
00:11:32,363 --> 00:11:35,201
What are you studying up there?

124
00:11:36,803 --> 00:11:38,121
The usual.

125
00:11:38,282 --> 00:11:41,200
You know. Nebulae, quasars, pulsars,
stuff like that.

126
00:11:41,362 --> 00:11:43,841
What are you...?
What are you writing?

127
00:11:44,002 --> 00:11:48,200
The usual. Nouns, adverbs,
adjective here and there.

128
00:11:49,481 --> 00:11:50,921
I work on a project called SETI.

129
00:11:51,681 --> 00:11:53,640
Search for Extraterrestrial Intelligence?

130
00:11:54,281 --> 00:11:57,719
Wow. Man, that is out there.

131
00:11:58,479 --> 00:12:00,239
Wait, are you a student or something?

132
00:12:00,399 --> 00:12:03,558
Mm-mm. I'm a writer.
I'm writing a book.

133
00:12:03,719 --> 00:12:08,199
Down here doing research about how
technology affects Third World cultures.

134
00:12:08,359 --> 00:12:11,078
I'm also looking for this guy
David Drumlin.

135
00:12:11,238 --> 00:12:15,517
He's the new head of the National Science
Foundation. I'm trying to get an interview.

136
00:12:16,358 --> 00:12:19,237
- I take it you know him?
- Mm-hm.

137
00:12:19,398 --> 00:12:21,277
You could say that.

138
00:12:22,078 --> 00:12:25,597
SETI, man.
That's fringe.

139
00:12:25,758 --> 00:12:27,237
I've crossed paths with this guy.

140
00:12:27,398 --> 00:12:29,957
Something like that
must really chap his ass, huh?

141
00:12:32,797 --> 00:12:34,117
Compass.

142
00:12:35,717 --> 00:12:37,236
For you, EI.

143
00:12:41,637 --> 00:12:43,356
You better keep this.

144
00:12:44,197 --> 00:12:46,235
Might save your life someday.

145
00:12:50,236 --> 00:12:51,956
Will you have dinner with me tonight?

146
00:12:53,436 --> 00:12:54,619
I...

147
00:12:54,876 --> 00:12:58,355
I don't make a very good research subject.
I'm just not very quotable.

148
00:12:58,516 --> 00:13:02,114
No quotes. No quotes. Scout's honor.
Just a good meal, good company.

149
00:13:02,916 --> 00:13:04,675
I gotta go.

150
00:13:07,755 --> 00:13:09,794
But, uh...
But...

151
00:13:12,954 --> 00:13:14,906
Drumlirs coming in this Tuesday.

152
00:13:23,233 --> 00:13:26,952
Now I remember why I took that desk job.

153
00:13:27,912 --> 00:13:30,352
- Dr. Drumlin, how are you?
- Dr. Drumlin.

154
00:13:31,273 --> 00:13:33,271
Glad you could make it, David.

155
00:13:33,712 --> 00:13:36,831
If I'd known it was gonna take
three planes, I might've reconsidered.

156
00:13:36,992 --> 00:13:38,311
How is that new office?

157
00:13:38,472 --> 00:13:42,871
I'm still settling in. They already wanna take
half my budget and give it to the Pentagon.

158
00:13:43,032 --> 00:13:45,791
Ellie. Still waiting for E.T. To call?

159
00:13:45,952 --> 00:13:49,791
- Well, I understand we're having a little...
- Good to see you too.

160
00:13:49,952 --> 00:13:50,911
Asshole.

161
00:13:51,071 --> 00:13:53,310
Uh-oh. Looks like
it's gonna be a long night.

162
00:13:53,471 --> 00:13:57,750
Science must first be accountable to the
people who are paying for it, the taxpayers.

163
00:13:57,911 --> 00:14:01,150
We need to stop wasting money
on pie-in-the-sky abstractions...

164
00:14:01,311 --> 00:14:04,149
...and start spending it on practical,
measurable ways...

165
00:14:04,310 --> 00:14:07,069
...to improve the lives of the people
who are footing the bill.

166
00:14:07,230 --> 00:14:10,229
Not unlike my L-band,
globular-clusters work.

167
00:14:10,390 --> 00:14:13,308
Wait, you're saying you wanna do away
with all pure research now?

168
00:14:13,470 --> 00:14:16,669
What's wrong with science being practical?
Even profitable?

169
00:14:16,869 --> 00:14:20,548
Nothing, as long as your motive
is the search for truth.

170
00:14:20,709 --> 00:14:23,708
Which is exactly what
the pursuit of science is.

171
00:14:25,189 --> 00:14:26,948
That's a rather interesting position...

172
00:14:27,109 --> 00:14:30,628
...coming from a man on a crusade
against the evils of technology...

173
00:14:30,789 --> 00:14:31,827
...Father Joss.

174
00:14:32,469 --> 00:14:34,747
I'm not against technology, doctor.

175
00:14:34,908 --> 00:14:38,986
I'm against the men who deify it
at the expense of human truth.

176
00:14:42,667 --> 00:14:45,746
Kent, I've been meaning to have
a word with you. Over here, please.

177
00:14:45,907 --> 00:14:47,705
Yeah, I'll just...

178
00:14:51,546 --> 00:14:54,545
I think that hurt my chances
with that interview. What do you think?

179
00:14:55,146 --> 00:14:56,904
You're a priest?

180
00:14:58,346 --> 00:14:59,544
No, not really.

181
00:15:00,185 --> 00:15:03,144
I got my Masters in Divinity...

182
00:15:03,306 --> 00:15:06,744
...then dropped out of seminary to
do some secular humanitarian work...

183
00:15:06,905 --> 00:15:09,304
...coordinating efforts
for Third World churches.

184
00:15:09,865 --> 00:15:12,424
I couldn't live with
the whole celibacy thing.

185
00:15:14,705 --> 00:15:16,024
You could...

186
00:15:16,185 --> 00:15:18,664
You could call me a man of the cloth...

187
00:15:19,464 --> 00:15:20,983
...without the cloth.

188
00:15:24,183 --> 00:15:25,783
You wanna get out of here?

189
00:15:27,623 --> 00:15:30,983
All right, you see that sort of large,
W-shaped constellation right there?

190
00:15:31,144 --> 00:15:32,542
That's Cassiopeia.

191
00:15:32,703 --> 00:15:37,062
And Cassiopeia A gives off
a whole lot of radio signals.

192
00:15:37,223 --> 00:15:41,542
I actually listen to them a lot.
It's a remnant of a supernova.

193
00:15:42,223 --> 00:15:44,982
When did you know
you wanted to be an astronomer?

194
00:15:45,462 --> 00:15:46,861
Well, when I...

195
00:15:47,022 --> 00:15:50,701
When I was about 8 years old,
I was watching the sunset...

196
00:15:50,862 --> 00:15:54,101
...and I asked my dad,
"What's that bright star over there?"

197
00:15:54,262 --> 00:15:56,820
Dad, what's that star there?

198
00:15:57,380 --> 00:16:00,340
And he said that it wasrt
really a star at all. It was actually...

199
00:16:00,501 --> 00:16:02,099
That's not a star, it's a planet.

200
00:16:02,261 --> 00:16:03,819
A whole planet called Venus...

201
00:16:03,980 --> 00:16:05,899
That's the planet Venus.

202
00:16:08,140 --> 00:16:11,939
Which should be over there soon.

203
00:16:12,100 --> 00:16:14,698
He said,
"You know why they called it Venus?"

204
00:16:14,860 --> 00:16:18,018
"Because they thought
it was so beautiful and glowing."

205
00:16:18,180 --> 00:16:20,178
"But what they didn't know..."

206
00:16:20,339 --> 00:16:22,858
"...is that it's filled with..."

207
00:16:24,019 --> 00:16:27,578
"...deadly gases and sulfuric acid rain."

208
00:16:28,579 --> 00:16:32,617
"Wow," I thought,
"This is it! I'm hooked."

209
00:16:34,099 --> 00:16:37,937
You know, there are four hundred billion
stars out there...

210
00:16:38,097 --> 00:16:40,257
...just in our galaxy alone.

211
00:16:40,577 --> 00:16:44,337
If only one out of a million
of those had planets...

212
00:16:44,498 --> 00:16:47,537
...all right, and ifjust one
out of a million of those had life...

213
00:16:47,697 --> 00:16:52,136
...and ifjust one out of a million
of those had intelligent life...

214
00:16:52,417 --> 00:16:57,216
...there would be literally millions
of civilizations out there.

215
00:16:58,576 --> 00:17:00,576
Well, if there wasrt...

216
00:17:00,977 --> 00:17:03,375
...it'd be an awful waste of space.

217
00:17:08,736 --> 00:17:10,415
Amen.

218
00:17:18,414 --> 00:17:23,212
So I was lying there,
just looking at the sky.

219
00:17:26,014 --> 00:17:29,692
And then I felt something.
I don't know, I...

220
00:17:30,174 --> 00:17:32,933
All I know is that I wasrt alone.

221
00:17:33,093 --> 00:17:37,812
And for the first time in my life
I wasrt scared of nothing, you know?

222
00:17:37,973 --> 00:17:39,852
Not even dying.

223
00:17:44,973 --> 00:17:46,931
It was God.

224
00:17:49,292 --> 00:17:51,531
And there's no chance that...

225
00:17:51,692 --> 00:17:55,771
...you had this experience because
some part of you needed to have it?

226
00:17:56,971 --> 00:18:00,331
I mean, I'm a reasonably intelligent guy,
but this...

227
00:18:03,051 --> 00:18:06,890
No, this... No, my intellect,
it couldn't even touch this.

228
00:18:07,051 --> 00:18:08,049
No.

229
00:18:10,410 --> 00:18:12,889
I've been to Sunday school a few times.

230
00:18:14,250 --> 00:18:15,929
Uh-huh. And?

231
00:18:16,090 --> 00:18:21,129
Well, I just kept asking all these
really annoying questions like:

232
00:18:21,290 --> 00:18:24,129
"All right, then where did Mrs. Cain
come from?"

233
00:18:25,369 --> 00:18:27,848
And pretty soon they called my dad
and they asked him...

234
00:18:28,010 --> 00:18:30,649
...if he wouldn't mind just
keeping me home from now on.

235
00:18:30,810 --> 00:18:32,768
Your dad...

236
00:18:33,690 --> 00:18:36,768
- Is it this guy?
- Yeah.

237
00:18:38,568 --> 00:18:40,927
You're close to him, aren't you?

238
00:18:41,768 --> 00:18:45,086
Yeah, I was.
He died when I was 9 years old.

239
00:18:46,887 --> 00:18:48,806
I never got to know my mother.

240
00:18:50,327 --> 00:18:51,606
I'm sorry.

241
00:18:55,926 --> 00:18:57,766
That's gotta be tough.

